Finland switched sides from Axis to Co-belligerent with the Allies in 1944.

Slovakia and Hungary both switched sides from Axis to Belligerents for the Axis but then became satellite states of Germany before eventually joining the German side, however they were later invaded by Soviet troops and subsequently occupied by them after changing their allegiance again, making it difficult to categorize as a switch in sides in the classical sense.

Italy initially remained loyal to the Axis but switched sides from Axis to Allied in 1943 after being invaded by German forces and eventually declared war on Germany.

Romania initially remained loyal to the Axis but switched sides from Axis to Allied in 1944 after changing their allegiance in response to the Soviet advance into Romania.

Bulgaria initially remained loyal to the Axis but switched sides from Axis to Allied in 1944 after changing their allegiance in response to the Soviet advance into Bulgaria.

Yugoslavia, which was a part of the Axis due to being occupied by Germany and Italy, switched sides from Axis to Co-belligerent with the Allies through Josip Broz Tito's Partisans who operated from 1941 until the end of World War II in Europe.
